        Lot Entitlements in a Queensland Body Corporate: What Unit Sellers Need to Understand
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Lot entitlements govern how much your buyer will pay in levies and how much say they will have in body corporate decisions. Understanding them helps you price your unit accurately and answer buyer questions with confidence.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When you sell a unit or townhouse in Queensland, the body corporate is part of the package. Buyers purchasing into a community titles scheme are not just buying the lot itself. They are buying into a shared governance structure, ongoing levy obligations, and rights over common property. Lot entitlements sit at the centre of all of this, and as a seller, you are expected to understand and disclose them. If you have not looked at your entitlement schedules before, now is a good time to start.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What lot entitlements are</h2>
      <p>Lot entitlements are numerical values assigned to each lot in a community titles scheme under the Body Corporate and Community Management Act 1997 (Qld). Every lot in a scheme has entitlements recorded on two separate schedules, and each schedule serves a different purpose.</p>

      <p>Schedule A is the Contribution Schedule. This schedule determines how body corporate expenses, including administrative fund levies and sinking fund levies, are divided among all lots in the scheme. A lot with a higher contribution entitlement pays a proportionally larger share of the total levies. Schedule B is the Interest Schedule. This schedule determines each lot's proportional share of the scheme's common property and assets, and also determines weighted voting rights at general meetings. A lot with a higher interest entitlement has a greater ownership stake in common areas and carries more weight in scheme decisions.</p>

      <p>The two schedules often have different values for the same lot, and that is intentional. The contribution entitlement is meant to reflect the relative benefit each lot gets from body corporate services, while the interest entitlement reflects the overall value and stake of the lot within the scheme.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How entitlements are set</h2>
      <p>Lot entitlements are set by the original developer when the community titles scheme is created and registered. The developer decides the values for each schedule based on factors like each lot's size, floor level, position in the building, access to views, car space allocations, and any exclusive use areas. A penthouse on the top floor with river views will typically carry a higher entitlement than a ground-floor unit of the same floor area. A unit with two car spaces may carry a higher entitlement than one with a single space.</p>

      <p>Once the scheme is registered and the first lots are sold, those entitlement values are locked into the scheme's community management statement. They do not change automatically over time, and they do not adjust when individual lots are renovated or when market values shift. A lot that was worth significantly less than its neighbours when the scheme was created may carry an entitlement that no longer reflects its current relative value, simply because no one has applied to change it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Can entitlements be changed?</h2>
      <p>Yes, but it is a high bar. Lot entitlements can be adjusted by a resolution without dissent at a general meeting, meaning every lot owner in the scheme must vote in favour or abstain. A single vote against the motion defeats it. Alternatively, an individual lot owner can apply to a specialist adjudicator or to a court to have entitlements adjusted if they can establish that the current values are unreasonable or incorrect. Both paths are time-consuming and procedurally demanding, and disputes over entitlements are among the most contested matters in body corporate law in Queensland.</p>

      <p>As a seller, this means the entitlements that apply to your lot when you sell are almost certainly the same ones that applied when the scheme was first created. You do not have the ability to renegotiate them before you list, and a buyer who believes the entitlements are unfair will need to pursue that process themselves after purchase. It is worth being upfront about this if it is relevant to your lot.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why entitlements matter for your sale</h2>
      <p>For buyers, contribution entitlements translate directly into levy amounts. The quarterly levies for a given lot are calculated by taking the total budget approved by the body corporate and allocating it according to each lot's contribution entitlement as a proportion of the total contribution schedule. A lot with a higher entitlement pays more. A lot with a lower entitlement pays less.</p>

      <p>This matters because buyers, particularly investor buyers, factor levy costs directly into their yield and affordability calculations. An investor purchasing a two-bedroom unit expecting to charge $700 per week in rent will look at the quarterly levies as a cost that reduces net yield. If your lot's contribution entitlement is disproportionately high relative to other lots in the scheme, the levy impost will be higher than a casual comparison of lot sizes might suggest. This can affect what an investor is willing to pay, even if the purchase price otherwise looks reasonable.</p>

      <p>Owner-occupiers care about levies too, but they also factor in interest entitlements when thinking about governance. A lot with a higher interest entitlement has more voting weight at general meetings. For buyers who intend to be active participants in scheme management, or who have concerns about how the body corporate is being run, this matters. For buyers who simply want to live in their unit and ignore the AGM entirely, it matters less.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What you need to disclose</h2>
      <p>Queensland law requires sellers of lots in community titles schemes to provide a disclosure statement to the buyer before or at the time of contract. The disclosure statement must include the lot's contribution and interest entitlements, the current levy amounts, information about any exclusive use by-laws affecting the lot, and details about the body corporate's financial position including any special levies. The seller's solicitor will prepare this document, drawing on the body corporate records search.</p>

      <p>The body corporate records search is the buyer's primary due diligence document. It includes the community management statement, the scheme's financial statements, details of outstanding levies, meeting minutes from recent general meetings, and information about any current or pending legal proceedings involving the scheme. Buyers who are serious will order this search and read it carefully. Your lot's entitlements and levy history will be plainly visible.</p>

      <p>If there are issues in the body corporate's records, such as a special levy that has been raised but not yet paid, outstanding maintenance matters, or disputes between lot owners, these will appear in the records search. It is better to be aware of what the search will reveal before you go to market, so you can anticipate buyer questions and address concerns proactively rather than reactively during negotiation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical takeaway for sellers</h2>
      <p>Before you list your unit, confirm your lot's contribution and interest entitlements from the community management statement and check what the current quarterly levies are. Your body corporate manager can provide these, and your solicitor will confirm the figures when preparing the disclosure statement. Knowing these numbers means you can have an informed conversation with buyers and your agent about positioning, particularly if your levies are higher than comparable units nearby.</p>

      <p>If your lot's entitlements sit at the higher end of the scheme, be realistic about how this affects investor appetite. A slightly higher levy is not necessarily a deal-breaker, but pretending it does not exist is not a useful strategy. Buyers will find it in the records search regardless, and a seller who has already addressed the question directly is easier to deal with than one who appears to have concealed relevant information.</p>

